message.content:
The start symbol S has only two possible productions:

1. S → NT68 NT63  
2. S → NT64 NT78   (with NT64 → NT60 NT14)

For every derivation the very first token of the generated string is produced by

• NT68 in the first alternative, or  
• NT60 in the second alternative.

NT68 directly generates only ‘t3’.  
NT60 directly generates ‘t3’ or ‘t5’, or the sequence NT68 NT18, whose first symbol is again NT68 → ‘t3’.

Thus, regardless of which production for S is chosen, the first symbol of every sentence in the language must be ‘t3’ (or ‘t5’).  
The given string begins with ‘t2’.

Consequently the string cannot be generated by this grammar.

No

The start symbol S can derive a string only through one of its two productions:

1. S → NT68 NT63  
   NT68 produces exactly one terminal, and every production for NT68 is
   NT68 → 't3'  
   Therefore any sentence derived through this rule must start with t3.
   The given string begins with t4, so this alternative is impossible.

2. S → NT64 NT78  
   NT64 derives NT60 NT14.  
   – The only terminal productions for NT60 are NT60 → 't3' and NT60 → 't5',  
     or NT60 → NT68 NT18 whose first symbol NT68 again produces 't3'.  
     Hence every derivation of NT64 necessarily starts with either t3 or t5.  

   Consequently, every sentence derived through S → NT64 NT78 must also begin
   with t3 or t5.  
   The given string still begins with t4, so this second alternative is
   likewise impossible.

Since the string cannot match the first terminal produced by either of the
only two possibilities for S, the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT68 NT63  
2. S → NT64 NT78  

Case 1:  
NT68 is a terminal rule NT68 → 't3', so the very first symbol of the string would have to be t3 (which it is), but NT63 must then derive the rest of the string.  
NT63 → NT84 NT62 and NT84 is restricted to the single-token productions  
 NT84 → 't3' | 't4'.  
Therefore the second symbol of the string must be either t3 or t4.  
The given string’s second symbol is t2, so derivation (1) is impossible.

Case 2:  
S → NT64 NT78.  
NT78 is fixed to the binary form NT78 → NT33 NT66 with NT66 → 't3'.  
Consequently every string generated via this branch must end in t3.  
The given string ends in t2, so derivation (2) is impossible.

Because both possible expansions for the start symbol fail to match the required fixed positions in the given string, the grammar cannot generate that string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT68 NT63  
   • NT68 has no further productions except NT68 → 't3'.  
   • Therefore the very first token of any string derived via this rule must be t3.

2. S → NT64 NT78  
   • NT78 → NT33 NT66 (its only binary rule).  
   • NT66 has no further productions except NT66 → 't3'.  
   • Hence the very last token of any string derived through this rule must be t3.

The string we are checking begins with t5 and ends with t0:

t5 … t0

Since it neither starts nor ends with t3, it cannot be generated by the first rule (needs initial t3) or by the second rule (needs final t3). Consequently the grammar cannot derive the given string.
